<div class="clearfix"></div>";i:2;s:0:"";i:3;s:0:"";i:4;s:8:"textarea";}s:15:"use_pdf_content";a:5:{i:0;s:15:"use_pdf_content";i:1;s:1:"1";i:2;s:0:"";i:3;s:0:"";i:4;s:16:"custom_tv:switch";}s:21:"overwrite_pdf_content";a:5:{i:0;s:21:"overwrite_pdf_content";i:1;s:0:"";i:2;s:0:"";i:3;s:0:"";i:4;s:16:"custom_tv:switch";}s:33:"issueArticleTranslationAuthorLink";a:5:{i:0;s:33:"issueArticleTranslationAuthorLink";i:1;s:0:"";i:2;s:0:"";i:3;s:9:"&format=,";i:4;s:18:"custom_tv:selector";}s:13:"pdf_footnotes";a:5:{i:0;s:13:"pdf_footnotes";i:1;s:20630:"<p><a href="#sdfootnote1anc" name="sdfootnote1sym">1</a> Georges Didi-Huberman, <em>Peuples exposés, peuples figurants: L’Œil de l’histoire, 4</em> (Paris: Les Éditions de Minuit, 2012), quoted in the pre-published excerpt: “People Exposed, People as Extras,” trans. Shane Lillisnotes, <em>Radical Philosophy</em> 156 (July/August 2009), 22. Another version of this excerpt with the same title is included in an exhibition catalog by the Argos art center: <em>Actors &amp; Extras</em>, eds. Paul Willemsen and Thomas Trummer (Brussels and Munich: Argos Centre for Art &amp; Media and Siemens Arts Program, 2009), 37–50.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote2anc" name="sdfootnote2sym">2</a> Ibid., 20.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote3anc" name="sdfootnote3sym">3</a> The English word “extras” hints at this economic dimension of the supernumeraries, “the fact that these are extra workers, as well as at the extra costs involved in film production.” Hedwig Saxenhuber, “‘Battles of Troy,’ ‘A Movie,’ and ‘Remote Resemblances,’ – A Gaze Deeply into the Collective Imaginative Space of the Cinema and Examination of Its Material Make-up,” in: <em>Extra Work: Krassimir Terziev. Taking the Figure of the Extra in Cinema Production as Metaphor</em>, ed. Jean Baptiste Joly (Stuttgart: Merz &amp; Solitude, 2008), 14.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote4anc" name="sdfootnote4sym">4</a> Vivian Sobchack, “‘Surge and Splendor’: A Phenomenology of the Hollywood Historical Epic,” <em>Representations</em> 29 (Winter 1990), 24–49.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote5anc" name="sdfootnote5sym">5</a> Cf. Kerry Segrave, <em>Extras of Early Hollywood: A History of the Crowd, 1913–1945</em> (Jefferson: McFarland, 2013); Anthony Slide, <em>Hollywood Unknowns: A History of Extras, Bit Players, and Stand-ins</em> (Jackson: University Press of Mississippi, 2012). On the history of the industrial organization of labor by actors and extras, particularly in Hollywood, see: <em>Combined Convention Proceedings National Alliance of Theatrical Stage</em> <em>Employees and Moving Picture Operators of the United States and Canada: A Record of All Conventions Held since the Inception of the Organization, July 1893</em> (New York: Musicians’ Press, 1926); Robert Osborne Baker, <em>The International Alliance of Stage Employees and Moving Picture Machine Operators of the United States and Canada</em> (Lawrence: University of Kansas, 1933); Alfred Harding, <em>Revolt of the Actors</em> (New York: W. Morrow &amp; Co., 1929); Murray Ross, <em>Stars and Strikes: Unionization of Hollywood</em> (New York: Columbia University Press, 1941); Louis B. Perry and Richard S. Perry, <em>A History of the Los Angeles Labor Movement, 1911–1941</em> (Berkeley, Los Angeles: University of California Press, 1963), 318–361 (chapter “Union Success in the Movie Industry”).</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote6anc" name="sdfootnote6sym">6</a> “Statisten,” in: <em>Theater-Lexikon: Theoretisch-Praktisches Handbuch für Vorstände, Mitglieder und Freunde des deutschen Theaters</em>, eds. Philipp Jakob Düringer and Heinrich Ludwig Barthels (Leipzig: Otto Wigand, 1841), 1010.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote7anc" name="sdfootnote7sym">7</a> “Comparsen,” in: <em>Theater-Lexikon</em>, op. cit., 220 (trans. by the author).</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote8anc" name="sdfootnote8sym">8</a> Roberto Esposito, <em>Communitas: The Origin and Destiny of Community</em>, trans. Timothy Campbell (Stanford: Stanford University Press, 2010), 4–8.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote9anc" name="sdfootnote9sym">9</a> R. K. Pruthi, <em>The Political Theory</em> (New Delhi: Sarup &amp; Sons, 2005), 110.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote10anc" name="sdfootnote10sym">10</a> Gottfried Achenwall, <em>Abriß der neuesten Staatswissenschaft der vornehmsten europäischen Reiche und Republicken zum Gebrauch in seinen Academischen Vorlesungen</em> (Göttingen: Joh. Wilhelm Schmidt, Univ. Buchhandl., 1749), <a href="http://www.deutschestextarchiv.de/book/show/achenwall_staatswissenschaft_1749" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http://www.deutschestextarchiv.de/book/show/achenwall_staatswissenschaft_1749</a>.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote11anc" name="sdfootnote11sym">11</a> Alain Desrosières, <em>The Politics of Large Numbers: A History of Statistical Reasoning</em>, trans. Camille Naish (Cambridge, MA and London: Harvard University Press, 1998), 147.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote12anc" name="sdfootnote12sym">12</a> Ibid.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote13anc" name="sdfootnote13sym">13</a> On the history of measures and their standardization in the course of the French Revolution and the abolition of feudalism, see the seminal study by Witold Kula, <em>Measures and Men</em>, trans. Richard Szreter (Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1986), 161–264.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote14anc" name="sdfootnote14sym">14</a> On the relationship between statistics and state control, see, e.g., Ian Hacking, “How Should We Do the History of Statistics?,” in: <em>The Foucault Effect: Studies in Governmentality</em>, eds. Graham Burchell, Colin Gordon, and Peter Miller (Chicago: University of Chicago Press, 1991), 181–195. On the history of statistics, see also: Ian Hacking, <em>The Emergence of Probability: </em><em>A Philosophical Study of Early Ideas about Probability, Induction and Statistical Inference</em> (London and New York: Cambridge University Press, 1975); Stephen M. Stigler, <em>The History of Statistics: The Measurement of Uncertainty before 1900</em> (Cambridge, MA, London: The Belknap Press of Harvard University Press, 1986); Anders Hald, <em>A History of Probability and Statistics and Their Applications before 1750</em> (Hoboken: Wiley, 1990); Anders Hald, <em>A History of Mathematical Statistics from 1750 to 1930</em> (New York: Wiley, 1998).</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote15anc" name="sdfootnote15sym">15</a> On this ambivalence of state measures aimed at social engineering and their failures throughout the twentieth century, see: James C. Scott, <em>Seeing Like a State: How Certain Schemes to Improve the Human Condition Have Failed</em> (New Haven and London: Yale University Press, 2008).</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote16anc" name="sdfootnote16sym">16</a> Alain Badiou, <em>Being and Event</em>, trans. Oliver Feltham (London and New York: Continuum, 2005), 23–30.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote17anc" name="sdfootnote17sym">17</a> Ibid., 99.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote18anc" name="sdfootnote18sym">18</a> Ibid., 178.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote19anc" name="sdfootnote19sym">19</a> Cf. Daniel W. Smith, “Mathematics and the Theory of Multiplicities: Badiou and Deleuze Revisited,” <em>Southern Journal of Philosophy</em> 41, no. 3 (2003), 411–449; Ray Brassier, “Badiou’s Materialist Epistemology of Mathematics,” <em>Angelaki</em> 10, no. 2 (2005), 135–150; B. Madison Mount, “The Cantorian Revolution: Alain Badiou and the Philosophy of Set Theory,” <em>Polygraph</em> 17 (2005), 41–91; Zachary Fraser, “The Law of the Subject: Alain Badiou, Luitzen Brouwer and the Kripkean Analyses of Forcing and the Heyting Calculus,” <em>Cosmos and History</em> 2, nos. 1–2 (2006), 94–133; Oliver Feltham, <em>Alain Badiou: Live Theory</em> (London and New York: Continuum, 2008); Sam Gillespie, <em>The Mathematics of Novelty: Badiou’s Minimalist Metaphysics</em> (Melbourne: re.press, 2008); Christopher Norris, <em>Badiou’s Being and Event: A Reader’s Guide</em> (London and New York: Continuum, 2009); Burhanuddin Baki, <em>Badiou’s Being and Event and the Mathematics of Set Theory</em> (London and New York: Bloomsbury, 2015); Arno Schubbach, “The State of a Situation and Badiou’s Mathematics,” in: <em>Badiou and the State</em>, ed. Dominik Finkelde (Baden-Baden: Nomos, 2017), 127–150.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote20anc" name="sdfootnote20sym">20</a> See: Alain Badiou, “Logic of the Site,” trans. Steve Corcoran and Bruno Bosteels, <em>Diacritics</em> 33, nos. 3–4 (Autumn–Winter 2003), 141–150; Alain Badiou, “The Paris Commune: A Political Declaration on Politics,” in: <em>Polemics</em>, trans. Steve Corcoran (London: Verso, 2006), 257–290; Alain Badiou, “The Paris Commune: A Political Declaration on Politics,” in: <em>The Communist Hypothesis</em>, trans. David Macey and Steve Corcoran (London: Verso, 2010), 168–228. On the Paris Commune as an example of the event in Badiou’s philosophy, see: Keith Bassett, “Thinking the Event: Badiou’s Philosophy of the Event and the Example of the Paris Commune,” <em>Environment and Planning D: Society and Space</em> 26 (2008), 895–910.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote21anc" name="sdfootnote21sym">21</a> Badiou, “The Paris Commune: A Political Declaration on Politics” (2006), 276.</p><div class="pagebreak"></div>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote22anc" name="sdfootnote22sym">22</a> See: Anne McCauley, <em>A. A. E. Disdéri and the Carte-de-visite Portrait Photograph</em> (New Haven and London: Yale University Press, 1985); Sylvie Aubenas, “Le petit monde de Disdéri: Un fonds d’atelier du Second Empire,” <em>Études photographiques</em> 3 (November 1997), <a href="http://journals.openedition.org/etudesphotographiques/93" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http://journals.openedition.org/etudesphotographiques/93</a>.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote23anc" name="sdfootnote23sym">23</a> Jules Claretie quoted in: Marc Gottlieb, <em>The Deaths of Henri Regnault</em> (Chicago and London: University of Chicago Press, 2016), 152. On photography and the Paris Commune, see: Gen Doy, “The Camera Against the Paris Commune,” in: <em>Photography/Politics: One</em>, eds. Terry Dennett and Jo Spence (London: Comedia Publishing Group, 1979), 12–21; Donald English, <em>Political Uses of Photography in the Third French Republic</em> (Ann Arbor: UMI Research Press, 1984), 69–70; André Rouillé, “Les images photographiques du monde de travail sous le Second Empire,” <em>Actes de la recherche en sciences sociales</em> 54 (September 1984), 41; Susan Buck-Morss, <em>The Dialectics of Seeing: Walter Benjamin and the Arcades Project</em> (Cambridge, MA and London: The MIT Press, 1989), 67; Christine Lapostolle, “Plus vrai que le vrai: Stratégie photographique et Commune de Paris,” <em>Actes de la recherche en sciences sociales</em> 73 (1988), 67–76; Christine Lapostolle, “La Commune de la barricade à la ruine,” <em>Recherches photographiques</em> 6 (1989), 20­–28; Jeannene M. Przyblyski, “Moving Pictures: Photography, Narrative, and the Paris Commune of 1871,” in: <em>Cinema and the Invention of Modern Life</em>, eds. Leo Charney and Vanessa R. Schwartz (Berkeley, Los Angeles, and London: University of California Press, 1995), 253–278; Jeannene M. Przyblyski, “Revolution at a Standstill: Photography and the Paris Commune of 1871,” <em>Yale French Studies</em> 101 (2001), 54–78.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote24anc" name="sdfootnote24sym">24</a> Didi-Huberman,<em> Peuples exposés, peuples figurants</em>, 99.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote25anc" name="sdfootnote25sym">25</a> See: Christian Phéline, <em>L’image accusatrice</em> (Paris: Cahiers de la photographie, 1985); Allan Sekula, “The Body and the Archive,” <em>October</em> 39 (Winter 1986), 1–64.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote26anc" name="sdfootnote26sym">26</a> “La participation active des comédiens à la réalisation de ce film constitue précisément ce qui fait peur aux médias mondiaux, et représente probablement l’une des raisons premières des refus de financement de la part des nombreuses chaînes de TV sollicitées pour apporter un soutien…” (trans. by the author).</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote27anc" name="sdfootnote27sym">27</a> Cf. the afterword to the publication that reissues Peter Watkins’s website in book form: Rebond pour La Commune, “Le Censure n’est plus ce qu’elle était: De <em>La Bombe</em> (1965) à <em>La Commune</em> (1999),” in: Peter Watkins, <em>Media Crisis</em>, trans. Patrick Watkins (Paris: Les Éditions l’échappée, 2015), 197.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote28anc" name="sdfootnote28sym">28</a> “Ce don’t les medias ont particulièrement peur, est de voir le petit homme du petit écran remplacé par une multitude de gens – par le public…” (trans. by the author).</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote29anc" name="sdfootnote29sym">29</a> Cf. the interview with Peter Watkins by Frédéric Bas, “Chacun devait écrire des dialogues,” <em>Cahiers du cinema</em> 546 (May 2000), 11. On the democratic process of production, cf. Michael Wayne, “The Tragedy of History: Peter Watkins’s <em>La Commune</em>,” <em>Third Text</em> 16, no. 1 (2002), 57–69; Michaela Pöschl, “‘… beyond the limitations of the rectangular frame’: <em>La Commune</em>, DV, 345 Min., Peter Watkins, 1999,” trans. Aileen Derieg, <em>Differences &amp; Representations </em>10 (2003), https://transversal.at/transversal/1003/poschl/en#_ftnref11; Roxanne Panchasi, “If the Revolution Had Been Televised: The Productive Anachronisms of Peter Watkins’s <em>La Commune (Paris, 1871)</em>,” <em>Rethinking History</em> 10, no. 4 (December 2006), 553–571; Antoine de Baecque, “The Watkins Way: History in Common,” in: <em>Camera Historica: The Century in Cinema</em>, trans. Ninon Vinsonneau and Jonathan Magidoff (New York: Columbia University Press, 2008), 192–200; Gabriel Levine, “Speech Across the Barricades: The Democratic Art of Peter Watkins’s <em>La Commune (Paris 1871)</em>,” <em>Public</em> 37 (Spring 2008), 120–129; Isabelle Marinone, “Une opposition aux mass media audiovisuels: <em>La Commune (Paris, 1871)</em>, une démarche alternative,” in: <em>L’insurrection médiatique: Médias, histoire et documentaire dans le cinéma de Peter Watkins</em>, eds. Sébastien Denis and Jean-Pierre Bertin-Maghit (Pessac: Presses Universitaires de Bordeaux, 2010), 49–61; François Bovier and Cédric Fluckiger, “Le langage de l’action politique dans <em>La Commune (Paris, 1871) </em>de Peter Watkins: ‘selmaire’ et utopie,” <em>Décadrages</em> 2 (2012), 92–109, <a href="https://doi.org/10.4000/decadrages.256">https://doi.org/10.4000/decadrages.256</a>.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote30anc" name="sdfootnote30sym">30</a> Cf. Watkins, <em>Media Crisis</em>, 28–38. On the concept of format, see in this context, e.g., Jonathan Sterne, “Format Theory,” in: <em>MP3: The Meaning of a Format</em> (Durham and London: Duke University Press, 2012), 1–31.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote31anc" name="sdfootnote31sym">31</a> Peter Watkins, “The Media Crisis: A Perspective by Peter Watkins,” <em>Tate</em>, September 2012, <a href="https://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-modern/peter-watkins-films-1964-99/media-crisis-perspective-peter-watkins" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.tate.org.uk/whats-on/tate-modern/peter-watkins-films-1964-99/media-crisis-perspective-peter-watkins</a>.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote32anc" name="sdfootnote32sym">32</a> Jean-Luc Godard in <em>La politique et le bonheur: Georges Kiejman</em> (1972), quoted after the English subtitles on the Criterion Collection DVD of <em>Tout va bien</em>, released in 2005. On this topic, see also: Hito Steyerl, “Können Zeugen sprechen? Zur Philosophie des Interviews,” in: <em>Die Farbe der Wahrheit: Dokumentarismen im Kunstfeld </em>(Vienna: Turia + Kant, 2008), 18–26, published in an English translation as “Can Witnesses Speak? On the Philosophy of the Interview,” trans. Aileen Derieg, <em>transversal texts</em>, May 2008, <a href="https://transversal.at/transversal/0408/steyerl/en" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://transversal.at/transversal/0408/steyerl/en</a>.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote33anc" name="sdfootnote33sym">33</a> Gayatri Chakravorty Spivak, “Can the Subaltern Speak?,” in: <em>Marxism and the Interpretation of Culture</em>, eds. Cary Nelson and Lawrence Grossberg (Basingstoke: Macmillan, 1988), 271–313.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote34anc" name="sdfootnote34sym">34</a> Cf. the website of Le Rebond pour la Commune, <a href="http://www.lerebond.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http://www.lerebond.org</a>. For brief information on the activities of the collective, see also the appendix “Rebond pour la Commune” to Watkins, <em>Media Crisis</em>, 193–194. For testimonies of members of the association who acted in the film, see: François Bovier and Sylvain Portmann, “Entretien avec plusieurs membres de l’association Rebond pour la Commune,” Geneva (Villa Baron), June 17, 2012, <em>Décadrages</em>, <a href="https://www.decadrages.ch/entretien-avec-rebond-pour-la-commune" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.decadrages.ch/entretien-avec-rebond-pour-la-commune</a>.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote35anc" name="sdfootnote35sym">35</a> Peter Watkins, “<em>La Commune (de Paris, 1871)</em>,” filmmaker’s website, <a href="http://pwatkins.mnsi.net/commune.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">http://pwatkins.<br>mnsi.net/commune.htm</a>.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote36anc" name="sdfootnote36sym">36</a> <em>The Universal Clock: The Resistance of Peter Watkins</em> (2001), directed by Geoff Bowie and produced by the National Film Board of Canada, <a href="https://www.nfb.ca/film/universal_clock_resistance_peter_watkins/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.nfb.ca/film/<br>universal_clock_resistance_peter_watkins/</a>.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote37anc" name="sdfootnote37sym">37</a> Kristin Ross, <em>Communal Luxury: The Political Imaginary of the Paris Commune</em> (London: Verso, 2015), 65.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote38anc" name="sdfootnote38sym">38</a> Alain Badiou, <em>Peut-on penser la politique?</em> (Paris: Éditions du Seuil, 1985), 68.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote39anc" name="sdfootnote39sym">39</a> Kristin Ross in an interview with Jerome Roos, “The Survival of the Paris Commune,” March 18, 2016, <em>Roar</em> no. 1 (Spring 2016), <a href="https://roarmag.org/magazine/kristin-ross-survival-paris-commune/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://roarmag.org/magazine/kristin-ross-survival-paris-commune/</a>.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote40anc" name="sdfootnote40sym">40</a> Kristin Ross, “Democracy for Sale,” in: Giorgio Agamben et al., <em>Democracy in What State?</em>, trans. William McCuaig (New York: Columbia University Press, 2011), 89. Ross is indebted here to Jacques Rancière’s thoughts on Joseph Jacotot’s method of intellectual emancipation, and indeed translated his essay <em>Le Maître ignorant</em> (1987): Jacques Rancière, <em>The Ignorant Schoolmaster</em>, trans. Kristin Ross (Stanford: Stanford University Press, 1991).</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote41anc" name="sdfootnote41sym">41</a> Ibid.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote42anc" name="sdfootnote42sym">42</a> Ross, <em>Communal Luxury</em>, 48.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote43anc" name="sdfootnote43sym">43</a> Cf. ibid., 2–4.</p><div class="pagebreak"></div>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote44anc" name="sdfootnote44sym">44</a> Kristin Ross in an interview with Joseph Confavreux, “Penser la Commune ‘comme autre mesure de la richesse sociale’,” <em>Mediapart</em>, January 31, 2015, <a href="https://www.mediapart.fr/journal/culture-idees/310115/penser-la-commune-comme-autre-mesure-de-la-richesse-sociale" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.mediapart.fr/journal/culture-idees/310115/penser-la-commune-comme-autre-mesure-de-la-richesse-sociale</a>, published in English as “The Contemporary Relevance of the Paris Commune,” trans. John Merrick, <em>Verso</em>, May 14, 2015, <a href="https://www.versobooks.com/blogs/1991-kristin-ross-the-contemporary-relevance-of-the-paris-commune" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.versobooks.com/blogs/1991-kristin-ross-the-contemporary-relevance-of-the-paris-commune</a>.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote45anc" name="sdfootnote45sym">45</a> Kristin Ross in an interview with Manu Goswami, “The Meaning of the Paris Commune,” <em>Jacobin</em>, April 5, 2015, <a href="https://www.jacobinmag.com/2015/05/kristin-ross-communal-luxury-paris-commune/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">https://www.jacobinmag.com/2015/05/kristin-ross-communal-luxury-paris-commune/</a>.</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote46anc" name="sdfootnote46sym">46</a> Bertolt Brecht, <em>Die Tage der Kommune</em> (Frankfurt am Main: Suhrkamp, 1966).</p>
<p><a href="#sdfootnote47anc" name="sdfootnote47sym">47</a> Didi-Huberman, “People Exposed, People as Extras,” 22.</p>";i:2;s:0:"";i:3;s:0:"";i:4;s:8:"textarea";}s:23:"overwrite_pdf_footnotes";a:5:{i:0;s:23:"overwrite_pdf_footnotes";i:1;s:0:"";i:2;s:0:"";i:3;s:0:"";i:4;s:16:"custom_tv:switch";}s:17:"use_pdf_footnotes";a:5:{i:0;s:17:"use_pdf_footnotes";i:1;s:1:"1";i:2;s:0:"";i:3;s:0:"";i:4;s:16:"custom_tv:switch";}s:7:"pdfFile";a:5:{i:0;s:7:"pdfFile";i:1;s:0:"";i:2;s:0:"";i:3;s:0:"";i:4;s:4:"file";}s:17:"__MODxSJScripts__";a:1:{i:1;s:120:"	<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="assets/templates/widok_tpl/minifyx/styles.min.4672983195df0c0237c3.css" />";}s:16:"__MODxJScripts__";a:2:{i:1;s:118:"	<script type="text/javascript" src="assets/templates/widok_tpl/minifyx/scripts.min.0e8961e12996bd7f5cde.js"></script>";i:2;s:170:"
